@Node "int4ch_commands" "Int4ch.guide/Commands"
@Toc "main"


 @{u}@{b}Commands@{uu}@{ub}

  01xx - Portamento Up
  02xx - Portamento Down
  03xx - TonePortamento
  04xx - Vibrato
  05xx - ToneP + VolSlide
  06xx - Vibra + VolSlide
  08xx - Arpeggio
  09xx - SampleOffset
  0Axx - VolumeSlide
  0Cxx - Set Volume
  11xx - Fineslide Up
  12xx - Fineslide Down
  1Axx - FineVol Up
  1Bxx - FineVol Down
  1Cxx - NoteCut


  @{u}@{b}Cmd 01. Portamento up [Speed:$00-$FF]@{uu}@{ub}

  Usage: $1 + portamento speed. Portamento up will simply slide the
  sample pitch up. You can NOT slide higher than B-3! (Period 113)

  Example: C-3 00 0103  1 is the command,
             3 is the portamentospeed.

  NOTE: The portamento will be called as many times as the speed of
  the song. This means that you'll sometimes have trouble sliding
  accuratly. If you change the speed without changing the sliderates,
  it will sound bad...


  @{u}@{b}Cmd 02. Portamento down [Speed:$00-FF]@{uu}@{ub}

  Usage: $2 + portamento speed

  Just like command 1, except that this one slides the pitch down
  instead. (Adds to the period).

  You can NOT slide lower than C-1! (Period 856)

  Example: C-3 00 0203  2 is the command, 3 is the portamentospeed.


  @{u}@{b}Cmd 03. Tone-portamento [Speed:$00-$FF]@{uu}@{ub}

  Usage: Dest-note + $3 + slidespeed

  This command will automatically slide from the old note to the new.
  You don't have to worry about which direction to slide, you need only
  to set the slide speed. To keep on sliding, just select the command
  $3 + 00.

  Example: A-2 00 0000  First play a note.
           C-3 00 0305  C-3 is the note to slide to, 3 the command,
                        and 5 the speed.


  @{u}@{b}Cmd 04. Vibrato [Rate:$0-$F,Dpth:$0-$F]@{uu}@{ub}

  Usage: $4 + vibratorate + vibratodepth

  Example: C-3 00 0481  4 is the command, 8 is the speed of the vibrato,
                        and 1 is the depth of the vibrato.

  To keep on vibrating, just select the command $4 + 00. To change the
  vibrato, you can alter the rate, depth or both.


  @{u}@{b}Cmd 05. ToneP + Volsl [Spd:$0-$F/$0-$F]@{uu}@{ub}

  Usage: $5 + upspeed + downspeed
 
  This command will continue the current toneportamento and slide the
  volume at the same time.

  Example: C-3 00 0503  3 is the speed to turn the volume down.

           C-3 00 0540  4 is the speed to slide it up.


  @{u}@{b}Cmd 06. Vibra + Volsl [Spd:$0-$F/$0-$F]@{uu}@{ub}

  Usage: $6 + upspeed + downspeed

  This command will continue the current vibrato and slide the volume at
  the same time.

  Example: C-3 00 0605  5 is the speed to turn the volume down.

           C-3 00 0640  4 is the speed to slide it up.


  @{u}@{b}Cmd 08. Arpeggio [Range:$0-$F/$0-$F]@{uu}@{ub}

  Usage: $0 + 1st halfnote add
            + 2nd halfnote add

  Arpeggio is used to simulate chords. This is done by rapidly
  changing the pitch between 3(or 2) different notes. It sounds
  very noisy and grainy on most samples, but ok on monotone ones.

  Example: C-3 00 0047  C-major chord:
          (C+E+G  or    C+4+7 halfnotes)
           C-3 00 0037  C-minor chord:
          (C+D#+G or    C+3+7 halfnotes)


  @{u}@{b}Cmd 09. Set SampleOffset [Offs:$00-$FF]@{uu}@{ub}

  Usage: $9 + Sampleoffset

  This command will play from a chosen position in the sample, and not
  from the beginning. The two numbers equal the two first numbers in the
  length of the sample. Handy for speechsamples.

  Example: C-3 00 0923  Play sample from offset $2300.


  @{u}@{b}Cmd 0A. Volumeslide [Speed:$0-$F/$0-$F]@{uu}@{ub}

  Usage: $A + upspeed + downspeed

  Example: C-3 00 0A05  5 is the speed to turn the volume down.

           C-3 00 0A40  4 is the speed to slide it up.

  NOTE: The slide will be called as many times as the speed of the song.
  The slower the song, the more the volume will be changed on each note.


  @{u}@{b}Cmd 0C. Set volume [Volume:$00-$40]@{uu}@{ub}

  Usage: $C + new volume

  Well, this old familiar command will set the current volume to your own
  selected. The highest volume is $40. All volumes are represented in hex.
  (Programmers do it in hex, you know!)

  Example: C-3 00 0C10  C is the command, 10 is the volume (16 decimal).


  @{u}@{b}Cmd 11. Fineslide up [Range:$00-$FF]@{uu}@{ub}

  Usage: $11 + value

  This command works just like the normal portamento up, except that it
  only slides up once. It does not continue sliding during the length of
  the note.

  Example: C-3 00 1101  Slide up 1 at the beginning of the note.

  (Great for creating chorus effects)


  @{u}@{b}Cmd 12. Fineslide down [Range:$00-$FF]@{uu}@{ub}

  Usage: $12 + value

  This command works just like the normal portamento down, except that
  it only slides down once. It does not continue sliding during the
  length of the note.

  Example: C-3 00 1206  Slide up 6 at the beginning of the note.


  @{u}@{b}Cmd 1A. FineVolslide up [Range:$00-$FF]@{uu}@{ub}

  Usage: $1A + value

  This command works just like the normal volumeslide up, except that
  it only slides up once. It does not continue sliding during the length
  of the note.

  Example: C-3 00 1A03  Slide volume up 1 at the beginning of the note.


  @{u}@{b}Cmd 1B. FineVolslide down [Range:$00-$FF]@{uu}@{ub}

  Usage: $1B + value

  This command works just like the normal volumeslide down, except that
  it only slides down once. It does not continue sliding during the length
  of the note.

  Example: C-3 00 1B06  Slide volume down 6 at the beginning of the note.


  @{u}@{b}Cmd 1C. Cut note [Value:$00-$FF]@{uu}@{ub} 

  Usage: $1C + Tick to Cut note at.

  This command will cut the note at the selected tick, creating extremely
  short notes.

  Example: C-3 00 F006  Set speed to 6.
           C-3 00 1EC3  Cut at tick 3 out of 6.

  Note that the note is not really cut, the volume is just turned down.

@EndNode
